my_data2017 <- read_excel("caigeyieldtrials2017_breadwheat_alldata.xlsx")

seeds = my_data2017$SOURCE
yield = my_data2017$GrainYieldtha
yield = as.numeric(yield)
genotype = as.factor(my_data2017$GID)
my_data2017 = my_data2017[!is.na(my_data2017$GrainYieldtha), ] #for removing na values.

2017

ggplot() + 
  geom_boxplot(data = my_data2017, mapping = aes(site, GrainYieldtha, fill=SOURCE)) + ggtitle("Performance of seed sources across locations")

Obeservations

Check still remains the best at all locations.The other sources tend to alternate.

Observations

Filler has a far lower spread compared to the other sources. We could investigate this as this consistency may be due to a specific gene. However this may be due to low sample size. Filler only had two entries so it is not useful for analysis due to this low sample size.

ICARDA has many outliers compared to the other sources. We could investiage this to determine if it is a certain gene thread which is causing these outliers.

Note: I have altered the dataset a bit. I changed the column names to remove spaces and weird symbols. I initially tried to use yield/kg but noticed that there were many missing values so I have swapped to yield t/ha. There were also a few NA values so they have been accounted for through the flag in tapply(“na.rm = TRUE”).

I tried graphing genotypes vs yield and while it worked, I do not think it will be useful as there are many genotypes. I am not sure what to do with this.

I manually deleted rows with NA values in the dataset as I am unsure how to deal with them. I will ask my mentors how to deal with this problem.

Graphs of best genotypes for each location

icarda_sub <- my_data2017 %>%
filter(SOURCE  == "ICARDA")
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4
#This creates the icarda_geno.
icarda_geno = icarda_sub %>%
        
      group_by(GID) %>%
      summarize(
      # averages
      mediangeno = median(as.numeric(GrainYieldtha))) %>%
        arrange(desc(mediangeno)) %>%
        slice(1:10) 

p <- ggplot(icarda_geno, aes(x = as.factor(GID), y=mediangeno, fill = as.factor(GID))) + 
    geom_bar(stat='identity') +
    
    labs(x = "Genotypes", y = "Yield") + ggtitle("Top genotypes for Icarda") + coord_flip()
print(p)

Observations

When plotting the best performing genotypes for Icarda, these genotypes all seem to start with 400… . This may have something to do with the genotype so we should investigate it further.

check_sub = my_data2017 %>%
  filter(SOURCE == "CHECK")

check_geno = check_sub %>%
        
      group_by(GID) %>%
      summarize(
      # averages
      mediangeno = median(as.numeric(GrainYieldtha))) %>%
        arrange(desc(mediangeno)) %>%
        slice(1:10)

    labs(x = "Genotypes", y = "Yield") + ggtitle("Top genotypes for Check")
